Indian Equity Movers: GTL, Hindustan Petroleum, Larsen, Mphasis

-- B y   S h i k h a r   B a l w a n i
-- 
2011-08-19T06:00:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-19/indian-equity-movers-gtl-hindustan-petroleum-larsen-mphasis.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 11:19 a.m. local time.  India ’s Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or Sensex,
lost 2 percent to 16,144.36, poised for its lowest close since
May 2010. The BSE200 Index retreated 1.7 percent to 2,003.02.  GTL Ltd. (GTS)  , a maker of telecommunication equipment,
tumbled 5.4 percent to 49 rupees, set for the lowest close since
May 2004, after reporting profit for the quarter ended June
declined to 129.3 million rupees ($2.8 million) from 351 million
rupees a year earlier.  Hindustan Petroleum Corp. (HPCL IN) climbed 2 percent to
386.70 rupees, set for the biggest gain in two weeks. The state-
run refiner is in talks with London-based BP Plc and Total SA of
 France  to revive the stalled $10-billion refinery and
petrochemicals project at Vizag in Andhra Pradesh state, the
 Press Trust of India  reported, citing an unidentified person.  Larsen & Toubro Ltd. (LT)  , the country’s biggest
engineering company, sank 4.5 percent to 1,554.50 rupees, headed
for the steepest drop in almost six months.  Mahindra & Mahindra
Ltd. (MM) , the biggest sports-utility vehicle maker, will replace
Larsen in Morgan Stanley’s Asia ex-Japan and Global Emerging
Market Focus Lists.  Mphasis Ltd. (MPHL)   dropped 4.2 percent to 343 rupees,
on course for the lowest close since June 2009.  Hewlett-Packard
Co. (HPQ)  , which owns a majority stake in the Indian software
maker, is planning a sweeping overhaul of its businesses,
agreeing to buy Autonomy Corp. for $10.3 billion. Hewlett-
Packard issued forecasts that missed estimates, saying it’s
considering spinning off its PC division and will discontinue
products that run WebOS software.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shikhar Balwani in Mumbai at 
 sbalwani@bloomberg.net ;  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 